metadata.name: Tempus Fugit #73
metadata.description:
This collection combines several classical techniques (Isometric 3D, voxels, noise fields, and unusual Truchet tilings) into something new.

In some pieces, the base 3d structure dissolves, creating an abstract, twisted painting
with only an elusive sense of the underlying construction logic.

Others are more architectural. Are they decaying cities from another age ? Deteriorating landscapes for the Minecraft generation ? Strange artifacts from a long gone alien civilization ? The viewer will decide.

All iterations, though, are designed to express this common feeling that time erodes everything. Tempus Fugit.


Made with p5.js only (no webgl).

Key commands:
's' - save to png
'1', '2, '4' - change resolution

metadata.name: Lucky Oracles #217
metadata.description:
"Lucky Oracles" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022

Eko33, is a Swiss-French generative artist who has been at the forefront of digital arts since 1999 when he started writing code to create generative artworks and installations. He made his debut using a Commodore SX-64 and floppy disks. Since then, his work has been exhibited in Museums, International art fairs, and biennales. His work is focused on nonfigurative, generative art while using custom algorithms and innovative technology.

Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/ Official Twitter account: https://twitter.com/eko3316 Official Instagram account: https://www.instagram.com/eko33studio/ https://linktr.ee/eko33 "I create deterministic generative art based on crypto hash seeds. Maximizing algorithmic diversity."

If you want to receive an e-mail alert when I release new artwork subscribe here => https://eko33.com/email-alerts

metadata.name: NESTED IDENTITIES #26
metadata.description:
Nested identities redact fingerprints but deeper meaning can still be found.

Nested identifies refers to the idea that a person may have multiple identities that are interconnected and interdependent. These identities may be related to a person's cultural background, ethnicity, nationality, gender, sexual orientation, social class, profession, and other factors. It is possible that a person may want to conceal or redact certain aspects of their identity in order to protect their privacy or to avoid discrimination or persecution. However, even if certain details about a person's identity are hidden or redacted, it may still be possible to infer deeper meaning or understand more about their experiences and perspectives based on the context in which they express themselves and the information that is available.


The concept of nested identities highlights the complexity and multifaceted nature of a person's identity, and how different aspects of identity can intersect and influence each other. It is important to recognize and respect the diversity of identities that people may hold, and to be mindful of the ways in which power dynamics and social context can shape how people present and express their identities. It is also important to recognize that people's identities may evolve and change over time, and that everyone has the right to self-identify and to define their own identity on their own terms.

Press p to download a high quality export.

metadata.name: The Fast Marching #96
metadata.description:
A signed distance function (SDF) is a mathematical function that describes the distance between a point in space and a fixed reference point or surface. The distance is signed, meaning it can be positive (outside the reference surface), zero (on the reference surface), or negative (inside the reference surface). SDFs are commonly used in computer graphics and robotics for collision detection, object representation, and path planning. They can also define complex shapes and perform Boolean operations on them. One of the most common algorithms to compute the SDF is known as the "Fast Marching Method."

Genuary 2023: Signed distance function

metadata.name: Foundations #41
metadata.description:
In march of this year, I started working on a new series involving multi-layering, and overriding shapes. Drawing and playing with colors and opacity.
It started with squares and grid, it then involved deformations, and circles and other experimentations.
This path fits with my artistic generative approach: rather than having a completely predefined idea, I start with a simple concept that evolves during creation. Then surprises happened, and I embraced them.

But this year was not like any other: 2022 has gifted me with a new birthday, the one of my son.

Over the past twelve months, I’ve watched him discovering the world surrounding him, learning and trying new things, laughing, or getting frustrated, sad or happy…
While learning to become a parent, I’ve been in an introspection phase where I questioned what it means to be “a father”. What impact will I have on my son, consciously or not?

“Foundations” takes shape in this context: 2 humans trying and exploring while being inspired by each other.
This series is a first of a set of at least 3, that illustrates an idea of what is an “Identity”, and what makes us who we are.

The foundations of an identity are laid in the first days of a child’s life. They will be influenced by many factors; including parenting, cultural environment, life experiences… 
Of course, as humans we are in constant evolution; life happens, sometimes for the best, sometimes for the worst, and our personality will be impacted…
But this will be a topic for another time. 


Today, we are at the start.

metadata.name: Dots #35
metadata.description:
Titled as a play with colors and shapes created from dots, Dots started as a collection on Objkt, extended to 8bidou and had new developments in Exchange Art. It was a dream to be able to make a collection of Dots on Fxhash, now it finally happened. Initially we only had 1 color palette, however, to create more variety, this project has 7 color palettes. To create the palettes we chose 5 famous artists to honor, including Peter Halley, Max Bill, Piet Mondrian, Sophie Taeuber and Lygia Clark, in addition to the palettes created by us. The project has several grids and some new possibilities in addition to the pieces already created on other platforms. It is with great pride and joy that we present this project made with great affection. Enjoy!

Press [S] to save a image

metadata.name: Shift #189
metadata.description:
A generative algorithm honing the power of vertical displacement.

How simple may a generative algorithm be while simultaneously staying diverse enough for each art piece to be truly unique? Shift is the result of an exploration into this space, basing its existence on two principles — dissection and vertical shifting. Each variable in this art engine has been meticulously weighted, giving rise to high diversity and the possibility of epic combinations. 

Shift is a series of 888 unique pieces.

############

Display resolution is 1000x1400. Press ’s’ (in live mode) to generate a 6000x8400 hi-res image. This may take a while to generate depending on your hardware.

Original artwork by perkwerk * made with p5.js * 2022

metadata.name: Blueprints of balance #43
metadata.description:
Balance in art is one of the basic principles of design, along with contrast, movement, rhythm, emphasis, pattern, unity, and variety. Balance refers to how the elements of art (line, shape, color, value, space, form, texture) relate to each other within the composition in terms of their visual weight to create visual equilibrium. That is, one side does not seem heavier than another.

But there is no balance without Chaos. And that is why for one hour everyday each Blueprint of balance let it go and turns into its alternative wild version.
